{"id": "spot-01-privacy", "question": "What did the Court hold on the right to privacy as a fundamental right?", "case_type": "holding", "expected_doc_ids": ["2024INSC790", "2024INSC835"], "expected_holding": "The right to privacy is a fundamental right, protected as an intrinsic part of the right to life and personal liberty under Article 21 and across the freedoms guaranteed by Part III of the Constitution. It is a multi-dimensional right encompassing spatial control, decisional autonomy, and informational control.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2024INSC790::472", "sc-2024INSC835::1498"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "What did the Court hold on the right to privacy as a fundamental right?", "notes": "VERIFIED (BORDERLINE - restatement case). The landmark is K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India (2017, nine-Judge Bench), which is OUTSIDE the 2018+ corpus, so every retrieval is a RESTATEMENT. 2024INSC790 (Society for Enlightenment and Voluntary Action v. UOI, child-marriage case, 18-Oct-2024) para 181 restates Puttaswamy's tripartite framing (spatial/decisional/informational); 2024INSC835 (Property Owners Association, 9J Art.39(b), Nov-2024) para 7 restates privacy as an Article 21 fundamental right. Both accurate. Holding is deliberately framed as the principle 'as held in Puttaswamy and restated in these judgments' - if you prefer, add 'restated in 2024INSC790/835, following Puttaswamy (2017)' explicitly to the holding text. Source: SCI / Bar&Bench / Lawctopus. SIGN-OFF: flip to human_verified."}
{"id": "spot-02-anticipatory-bail", "question": "What is the test for granting anticipatory bail?", "case_type": "issue", "expected_doc_ids": ["2024INSC202"], "expected_holding": "The power to grant anticipatory bail is an extraordinary power that is not to be exercised as a matter of rule; it is to be granted only in exceptional circumstances, with the court having regard to factors such as the nature and gravity of the accusation.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2024INSC202::78"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "What is the test for granting anticipatory bail?", "notes": "VERIFIED + REFRAMED (weakest of the set). 2024INSC202 (Srikant Upadhyay v. State of Bihar, 14-Mar-2024) para 24 states anticipatory bail is an extraordinary power, not the rule (same line quoted in 2025INSC477 para 25). IMPORTANT: retrieval for this query is fragmented across sub-issues (territorial jurisdiction 2023INSC1008; Section 82 proclamation 2024INSC202; corruption 2025INSC320) and did NOT cleanly surface the classic multi-factor Gurbaksh Singh Sibbia / Sushila Aggarwal test. So this holding is the nature/threshold principle, NOT the factor-list the question implies. OPTIONS: (a) accept this narrowed holding; (b) re-run retrieval with a query like 'Sibbia factors anticipatory bail nature gravity antecedents flight risk' to surface the factor-test, then re-pick the chunk; (c) defer this case. (Srikant Upadhyay also held that once a Section 82 proclamation is issued, anticipatory bail is ordinarily refused.) Source: SCI / LawWeb. SIGN-OFF: your call - consider option (b) before flipping."}
{"id": "spot-03-quash-fir", "question": "When can a High Court quash an FIR under its inherent powers?", "case_type": "issue", "expected_doc_ids": ["2024INSC846", "2024INSC750"], "expected_holding": "The High Court's inherent power to quash an FIR or criminal proceeding on the basis of a settlement between the offender and the victim is distinct from the power to compound offences under Section 320 CrPC, and is exercised to secure the ends of justice or to prevent abuse of the process of court. However, heinous and serious offences that are not private in nature and have a serious impact on society (such as sexual offences against a child under the POCSO Act) cannot be quashed merely because the parties have compromised.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2024INSC846::101", "sc-2024INSC750::74"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "When can a High Court quash an FIR under its inherent powers?", "notes": "VERIFIED against published judgment. Para 61 in both 2024INSC846 (Ramji Lal Bairwa, 07-Nov-2024) and 2024INSC750 (K. Bharthi Devi) quotes the Gian Singh v. State of Punjab (2012) formulation verbatim. CORRECTED from draft: (1) the contrast is with COMPOUNDING under S.320, not 'appellate/revisional powers'; (2) scope narrowed to compromise-based quashing + the heinous-offence limit, which is what the chunk actually states. Source: LiveLaw / SCI judgment text. SIGN-OFF: flip to human_verified if you agree."}
{"id": "spot-04-judicial-review", "question": "What is the scope of judicial review of administrative action?", "case_type": "issue", "expected_doc_ids": ["2024INSC126", "2025INSC1108"], "expected_holding": "Judicial review of administrative action is qualitatively distinct from civil remedies and is concerned with the legality of the exercise of State power - checking whether a decision was made lawfully and is free of arbitrariness, irrationality, unreasonableness, bias and mala fides - not with the merits of the decision itself.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2024INSC126::40", "sc-2025INSC1108::116"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "What is the scope of judicial review of administrative action?", "notes": "VERIFIED clean against published judgment. 2024INSC126 (Manoj Kumar v. UOI, 20-Feb-2024) para 17 confirmed verbatim ('qualitatively distinct from judicial remedies in civil law ... concerned with the exercise of power by the State'). Grounds half matches 2025INSC1108 para 22 and standard Tata Cellular doctrine. Holding accurate, no change. Optional: cross-check 2025INSC1108 full para 22. SIGN-OFF: flip to human_verified."}
{"id": "spot-05-pmla-bail", "question": "What are the twin conditions for bail under the PMLA?", "case_type": "issue", "expected_doc_ids": ["2024INSC217"], "expected_holding": "Section 45(1) PMLA imposes twin mandatory conditions for the grant of bail: (i) the court must be satisfied that there are reasonable grounds for believing the accused is not guilty of the offence, and (ii) that the accused is not likely to commit any offence while on bail.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2024INSC217::80"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "What are the twin conditions for bail under the PMLA?", "notes": "VERIFIED + CORRECTED. 2024INSC217 (Satyendar Kumar Jain v. ED, 18-Mar-2024) confined itself to the S.45 PMLA twin conditions - clean PMLA authority. DROPPED 2025INSC477 (SFIO v. Aditya Sarda) from this case: it concerns the ANALOGOUS Companies Act s.212(6) twin conditions for s.447 fraud, not PMLA s.45 (could anchor a separate Companies Act golden case later). CONFIRM 2024INSC217 para 13 enumerates BOTH conditions (i) and (ii) in full (snippet truncates after (i)). Source: SCC / SCI. SIGN-OFF: flip to human_verified."}
{"id": "spot-06-reservation-promotions", "question": "What did the Court hold on reservation in promotions for public employment?", "case_type": "holding", "expected_doc_ids": ["2023INSC613"], "expected_holding": "Persons with disabilities are entitled to reservation in promotions in public employment. The bar recognised in Indra Sawhney - that Article 16(4) reservation for backward classes is confined to the initial appointment and does not extend to promotion - does not apply to disability-based reservation, which rests on the distinct principle of reasonable accommodation under the Persons with Disabilities Act, 1995 and the Rights of Persons with Disabilities Act, 2016. The absence of rules providing for such reservation in promotion does not absolve the State from identifying posts and granting it.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2023INSC613::227"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "What did the Court hold on reservation in promotions for public employment?", "notes": "VERIFIED + CORRECTED (original generic framing was wrong). 2023INSC613 is Reserve Bank of India v. A.K. Nair (04-Jul-2023) - specifically reservation in PROMOTIONS for PERSONS WITH DISABILITIES, NOT the general SC/ST Nagaraj/Jarnail Singh line. It upholds PwD promotion reservation and DISTINGUISHES Indra Sawhney. WARNING on chunks: the high-scoring chunk sc-2023INSC613::178 states the Indra Sawhney OBC rule (the OPPOSITE principle) and must NOT be used as support; sc-2023INSC613::227 (the Leesamma Joseph PwD affirmation) is the correct holding-bearing chunk. Retrieval is history-heavy; the operative ratio paragraph (Section 20 RPwD Act 2016 / reasonable accommodation / Indra Sawhney distinguished) should be confirmed/added from the full judgment. Source: LiveLaw / SCObserver / SCI. SIGN-OFF: flip to human_verified after confirming the chunk."}
{"id": "spot-07-confession-police", "question": "When is a confession made to a police officer admissible in evidence?", "case_type": "issue", "expected_doc_ids": ["2025INSC376"], "expected_holding": "A confession made to a police officer is generally inadmissible under Section 25 of the Evidence Act (now Section 23 BSA). It is admissible only where a specific statute overrides the Evidence Act - here, Section 15 of TADA - and even then only if the confession was recorded with the safeguards prescribed by that statute and is proved to be voluntary and free of any trap, inducement or coercion.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2025INSC376::74", "sc-2025INSC376::55"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "When is a confession made to a police officer admissible in evidence?", "notes": "VERIFIED + REFINED against published judgment. 2025INSC376 (State (CBI) v. Mohd Salim Zargar @ Fayaz, 20-Mar-2025) is the 1990 KU VC Mushir-ul-Haq murder / TADA case; CBI's appeal against acquittal dismissed because the confessions were not shown to be voluntary/safeguarded. Para 16 = S.25 bar; para 15 = TADA s.15 exception (validity upheld in Kartar Singh v. State of Punjab). CORRECTED from draft: the exception here is TADA s.15, NOT S.27 - S.27 is genuine general law but is not in the cited chunks, so it is omitted from the holding for citation integrity. Source: LiveLaw / Greater Kashmir / SCI. SIGN-OFF: flip to human_verified."}
{"id": "spot-08-basic-structure", "question": "What is the doctrine of the basic structure of the Constitution?", "case_type": "issue", "expected_doc_ids": ["2024INSC554"], "expected_holding": "The basic structure doctrine, propounded by the thirteen-Judge Bench in Kesavananda Bharati v. State of Kerala (1973), holds that Parliament's power to amend the Constitution under Article 368 is subject to an implied limitation: an amendment cannot damage, destroy or alter the basic structure or essential features of the Constitution.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2024INSC554::771"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "What is the doctrine of the basic structure of the Constitution?", "notes": "VERIFIED (BORDERLINE - restatement case). The landmark is Kesavananda Bharati (1973), OUTSIDE the corpus, so retrievals are RESTATEMENTS. 2024INSC554 (Mineral Area Development Authority, 9J mineral-taxation case, 25-Jul-2024) para 226 accurately restates the doctrine as an implied limitation on the Article 368 amending power. WARNING on chunks: the 2024INSC831 (Anjum Kadari, madrasa case) chunks that scored high address a NARROWER sub-issue - whether the basic structure doctrine can invalidate ORDINARY legislation (it cannot; ordinary laws are tested against Part III / legislative competence) - so they must NOT anchor the general doctrine holding. 2024INSC835 para 143 illustrates one recognised basic feature (FR-DPSP harmony) if you want a second cite. Source: SCI / standard constitutional law. SIGN-OFF: flip to human_verified."}
{"id": "spot-09-article-22-arrest", "question": "What are the rights of an arrested person under Article 22?", "case_type": "issue", "expected_doc_ids": ["2025INSC768", "2025INSC162"], "expected_holding": "Informing an arrested person of the grounds of arrest is not a mere formality but a mandatory constitutional requirement under Article 22(1); failure to communicate the grounds violates the fundamental rights guaranteed under Articles 22 and 21 and renders the arrest illegal.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2025INSC768::97", "sc-2025INSC162::87"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "What are the rights of an arrested person under Article 22?", "notes": "VERIFIED clean against published judgment. 2025INSC162 (Vihaan Kumar v. State of Haryana, 07-Feb-2025) is the landmark ruling: grounds of arrest = mandatory Art. 22(1) requirement; non-communication renders the arrest illegal and also violates Art. 21. 2025INSC768 (Kasireddy Upender Reddy) quotes Vihaan Kumar para 14. Holding accurate. Optional enrichment: communication must be meaningful, in a language understood, preferably in writing (Pankaj Bansal lineage), burden on the arresting agency. Source: LiveLaw / Verdictum / SCI. SIGN-OFF: flip to human_verified."}
{"id": "spot-10-circumstantial-evidence", "question": "What is the standard of proof for circumstantial evidence in a criminal trial?", "case_type": "issue", "expected_doc_ids": ["2023INSC48", "2023INSC240"], "expected_holding": "In a case resting on circumstantial evidence, the prosecution must prove each circumstance beyond reasonable doubt, and the proved circumstances must form a complete chain that points only to the guilt of the accused and excludes every reasonable hypothesis consistent with innocence.", "supporting_chunk_ids": ["sc-2023INSC48::67", "sc-2023INSC240::14"], "verification_status": "machine_bootstrapped", "source_query": "What is the standard of proof for circumstantial evidence in a criminal trial?", "notes": "VERIFIED clean against published judgment. 2023INSC48 (Jabir v. State of Uttarakhand, 17-Jan-2023, Bhat & Narasimha JJ) para 21 confirmed verbatim ('prove each circumstance, beyond reasonable doubt, as well the links between all circumstances'); also limits the 'last seen' doctrine. 2023INSC240 (Guna Mahto v. State of Jharkhand) para 7 confirmed verbatim ('must point out only towards one hypothesis, that is, the guilt of the accused alone and none else'). Holding accurate (classic Sharad Birdhichand Sarda chain). Source: SCC / LiveLaw. SIGN-OFF: flip to human_verified."}
